We evaluated the accuracy of the novel probe by determining the fluorescence of TAP on spiked samples of milk, fish and tap water and found recoveries of 92.08%–108.4%, with a corresponding relative standard deviation of less than 3.74% (Table 2
                        ). HPLC detected similar results in the spiked samples with the developed sensing probe (R
                        2 = 0.9949) (Figs. S7 and S8), confirming the accuracy and reliability of N,S-CDs@MIPs as an optosensor probe for TAP analysis. Compared to previously reported sensors, the N,S-CDs@MIPs sensing probe had a lower low detection limit (LOD) of 6.20 μg/L, with better or comparable recovery and precision (Table 3
                        ). Due to its selection specificity of the molecularly imprinted layer, the sensitivity and selectivity of our sensing probe was better than UV–Vis spectrophotometric methods. The chromatographic and electrochemical methods also require sophisticated instruments and complex pretreatment processes, reducing their detection efficiency far less than our probes. Although Fe3O4@SiO2‒MIPS and CdTe*CdS*ZnS-QDs@MIPs were equally sensitive and effective, our novel probe is simple, low-cost and more environmentally friendly due to the use of only food waste instead of heavy metal compounds. The detection process also does not require expensive antibodies or enzymes like ELISA methods. The probe also achieves desired goals in only 30 min and is selective in detecting trace levels of TAP in food.
